### Generic Classes in C#

Generic classes encapsulate operations that are not specific to a particular data type.

### Declaration

```csharp
public class GenericClass<T>
{
    private T data;

    public GenericClass(T value)
    {
        data = value;
    }

    public T GetValue() => data;
    public void SetValue(T value) => data = value;
}

// Usage
var intHolder = new GenericClass<int>(42);
var stringHolder = new GenericClass<string>("Hello");
```

### Multiple Type Parameters

```csharp
public class Pair<TFirst, TSecond>
{
    public TFirst First { get; }
    public TSecond Second { get; }

    public Pair(TFirst first, TSecond second)
    {
        First = first;
        Second = second;
    }

    public void Deconstruct(out TFirst first, out TSecond second)
    {
        first = First;
        second = Second;
    }
}

var pair = new Pair<int, string>(1, "one");
```

### Generic Classes with Constraints

```csharp
public class NumericCalculator<T> where T : struct, IComparable, IConvertible
{
    public T Add(T a, T b)
    {
        dynamic da = a;
        dynamic db = b;
        return (T)(da + db);
    }
}
```

### Generic Collection Classes in .NET

```csharp
List<T>           // Dynamic array
Dictionary<TKey, TValue>  // Key-value pairs
Queue<T>          // FIFO collection
Stack<T>          // LIFO collection
HashSet<T>        // Unique elements
LinkedList<T>     // Doubly-linked list
SortedList<TKey, TValue>  // Sorted key-value
SortedSet<T>      // Sorted unique elements
```

### Generic Inheritance

```csharp
public class Base<T>
{
    public T Value { get; set; }
}

// Specify type in derived class
public class StringDerived : Base<string> { }

// Keep type parameter in derived class
public class GenericDerived<T> : Base<T> { }
```

### Static Members in Generic Classes

Static members are unique per type parameter combination:

```csharp
public class Counter<T>
{
    public static int Count = 0;
}

Counter<int>.Count++;     // Different from
Counter<string>.Count++;  // Counter<string>.Count
```

> **Key Point:** Generic classes are instantiated with specific type arguments. Static members are per constructed type. Generic classes can serve as base classes. The .NET framework provides many built-in generic collection classes.

### Factory Pattern with Generics

```csharp
public class Factory<T> where T : new()
{
    public static T Create() => new T();
}

var obj = Factory<MyClass>.Create();
```

### Generic Class vs Generic Method

| Aspect | Generic Class | Generic Method |
|--------|---------------|----------------|
| Scope | Entire class | Single method |
| Type parameter | Class-level | Method-level |
| When to use | Multiple methods share type | One method needs generics |
| State | Can hold typed fields | No typed state (unless captured) |

